					        <div id="comment-22534" class="a_comment">
				<p>Bengie25 - this is *exactly* how Toyota's Hybrid Synergy Drive works. There are no belts, but there are two electric motors. One on the flywheel of the petrol engine and another attached to what this dude calls the "control shaft" </p>
<p></p>
<p>It is effectively a differential with a motor on each end, with the wheels attached to what would be the input shaft on a classic differential. </p>
<p></p>
<p>You can then push the power on the output however you like by changing the control motors speed relative to the power motor (which, thanks to running on petrol, only has a limited speed range to work with). </p>
<p></p>
<p>There is nothing new under the sun. </p>
<p></p>
<p>q: Does anyone know what they're talking about? a: not you, at least. </p>
