					        <div id="comment-22549" class="a_comment">
				<p>There is no flywheel here. Please read p. 19 of the 2008 independent lab report hosted on Durnin's own web site: </p>
<p></p>
<p><a target="_blank" rel="nofollow" href="http://infinitelyvariabletransmission.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/dDrive-Transmission-Report.pdf">http://infinitelyvariabletransmission.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/dDrive-Transmission-Report.pdf</a> </p>
<p></p>
<p>They state clearly that this device acts as nothing more than an epicyclic gear set, and that it is not a CVT (though it could serve as part of one). It's a pretty decent analysis, which properly notes that it's actually arbitrary which input shaft you call "power" and which "control", since they both require comparable output motors. </p>
<p></p>
<p>With all due respect, I hereby recommend that GizMag admit that this device is a hoax, that they have made a mistake in featuring it, and formally retract the article. </p>
